******
[2] Merpanaikadu, Tamil Nadu state
Date: Mon 22 Sep 2014
Source: The Hindu [edited]
http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Tiruchirapalli/40-treated-for-symptoms-of-chikungunya/article6431949.ece


As many as 40 residents of Merpanaikadu, an interior village on the border of Pudukottai and Thanjavur districts, have shown symptoms of chikungunya [virus infection] over the past few days. Special health teams from the primary health centres in Aranthangi block, including Nagudi, camped in the village and provided treatment. "The situation is under control; however, a health team has been deployed in the village to keep a close watch," an official source said.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Chikungunya virus transmission has been very active in Tamil Nadu this month (September 2014). There have been 3 localities affected in the state.

Chikungunya virus is endemic in India. There were scattered outbreaks of chikungunya virus infections in several localities around India last year (2013). A report last year was the 1st one of an outbreak in Tamil Nadu state that has come to ProMED's attention. Now, we have the 3rd and 4th outbreaks reported above. It is not clear whether the diagnoses of chikungunya virus infection are based solely on clinical grounds or whether some or all cases are laboratory diagnosed as well. Cleaning or eliminating water containers is a prudent way to affect vector mosquito control. One hopes that the intensive cleanup campaign being launched successfully reduces the numbers of vector mosquitoes and transmission rates.

Maps of India can be seen at http://www.mapsofindia.com/images2/india-map.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2798819,41078. - Mod.TY]
